  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "1ce4750c-f3ba-809e-8217-fd60fc818b9b",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Task",
          "Context",
          "Student Performance Definition",
          "Target",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Features",
          "Flaw of Previous Models",
          "Novelty of Model",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Intelligent Tutoring System",
          "NExt Candidate Question is Answerewd Correctly",
          "Correct (1) vs Incorrect (0)",
          "1610 ASSISTments learners, 2648 AICFE-CM learners, 1451 AICFE-GE learners, 2445 AICFE-MA learners, 964 AICFE-PH learners",
          "ASSISTments, AICFE",
          "Sequence of Questions, Sequence of Answers",
          "[Student-Question Matrix, Question-Concept Mapping, Ordered Pairs]",
          "The idea of prerequisite knowledge between different knowledge concepts is underexplored in common KT frameworks. ",
          "Model proposed treats prequesities ar ordering pairs. Essencially, the probability of mastering a concept needs to be lower than the probability of having mastered concepts that are prequisites. ",
          "The first step starts with the building of 2 matrices:\n\nA student-question matrix indicating whether the question was correctly or incorrectly answered.\n\nA Question-Concept Mapping intending to identify which concepts are associated with each question.\n\nA set of pre-requisite relationships derived from ppedagogical experts. \n\nModelling of these constraints is attempted in different forms:\n\n1. Logic, 2. Boolean Factors and 3. A Conditional Probability, 4. An Ordering Pair",
          "BKT, DKT, PMF, PDKT-C",
          "10-Repeated Holdout",
          "AST\n{AUC: 0.805 - PDKT-C, Accuracy: 0.73 - PDKT-C, MAE: 0.37 - PDKT-C, RMSE: 0.43 - PDKT-C}\n\nAICFE-CM\n{AUC: 0.83 - PDKT-C, Accuracy: 0.76 - PDKT-C, MAE: 0.345 - PDKT-C, RMSE: 0.41 - PDKT-C}\n\nAICFE-GE\n{AUC: 0.82 - PDKT-C, Accuracy: 0.75 - PDKT-C, MAE: 0.35 - PDKT-C, RMSE: 0.42 - PDKT-C}\n\nAICFE-MA\n{AUC: 0.79 - PDKT-C, Accuracy: 0.75 - PDKT-C, MAE: 0.37 - PDKT-C, RMSE: 0.43 - PDKT-C}\n\nAICFE-PH\n{AUC: 0.795 - PDKT-C, Accuracy: 0.73 - PDKT-C, MAE: 0.36 - PDKT-C, RMSE: 0.44 - PDKT-C}",
          "The main difference of this approach relative to DKT is that it includes constraints on pre-requisite knowledge.\n\nOn all datasets, the authors show that PDKT-C is the most effective method out of all tested across all datasets.\n\nAuthors also do an Ablation study to check the effect of different parameter changes to model performance: \n-Hidden Units, Lambda, Trainig dataset size, Number oif considered pre-requisites.",
          "Does not consider additional sources of data,\n\nPre-requisite extraction needs optimization."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
  ],
